Despite the many years I lived in London, I must confess I never dared to journey up to the district of Whitechapel. For the well-born, these ill-famed streets only mean inequity, violence, poverty, and vice… Not to mention the infamous killer, whose nickname will forever taint that place. Yes, for many decades Whitechapel suffered from an awful reputation, constantly brought back by the horrid stories regaled by the news.  And I'm afraid the war and the epidemic only made those tales more tangible.
column3: Despite the many years I lived in London, I must confess I never dared to journey up to the district of Whitechapel. For the well-born, these ill-famed streets only mean inequity, violence, poverty, and vice… Not to mention the infamous killer, whose nickname will forever taint that place. Yes, for many decades Whitechapel suffered from an awful reputation, constantly brought back by the horrid stories regaled by the news.  And I'm afraid the war and the epidemic only made those tales more tangible.

column2: This recipe creates a treatment against Anaemia. It could also cure fatigue.

column2: The Whitechapel police have been informed of the mysterious disappearance of Edgar Swansea aged 45, physician, at approximately 6:30 this morning. The police have circulated a description of the missing man: height 6ft, slender build, fair complexion, greying hair, thin moustache; likely wearing a white surgeon coat, with dark flannelette vest and Oxford shirting, and leather evening shoes.<lf>Dr. Swansea is a familiar figure in the Whitechapel district: The current head of the Pembroke Hospital and a preeminent scientist. He spearheaded the mass admission of patients during last summer's flu epidemic. Although his methods have been criticized, it should be noted that Dr. Swansea did save a substantial number of individuals during the outbreak. His guidance drove the Pembroke to new technical heights, especially due to his enlistment of vanguard talents. His latest recruit was the transfusion pioneer, Doctor Jonathan E. Reid, who had recently returned from the war. The famous surgeon was nowhere to be found to answer our questions.<lf>The lack of a head surgeon has led to a drastic drop in the operation success rate at Pembroke. I would advise against entrusting yourself to them until Dr. Swansea is found, or a new head emerges to lead the hospital.<lf>E.W.

column2: Be careful when you sell items as some ingredients are hard to gather, and may be vital for unlocking, and crafting advanced recipes.

column2: Extra ammo will be stored in your stash.
column3: Додаткові набої зберігатимуться у вашому схроні.

column2: Hideouts are often located in isolated places. Find them to unlock new safe places to rest.
column3: Укриття часто розташовані в усамітнених місцях. Знайдіть їх, щоб відкрити нові безпечні місця для відпочинку.

column2: If a district’s Health Status drops below the Critical Threshold, it will plunge into chaos. Citizens will be reported missing, their quests will be lost, and dangerous creatures will begin to roam the streets.
column3: Якщо стан здоров'я району опуститься нижче критичного порогу, він зануриться в хаос. Містяни вважатимуться зниклими безвісти, їхні завдання будуть втрачені, а вулицями почнуть блукати небезпечні істоти.

column2: If you’re not strong enough, remember that the blood of Citizens is the fastest way to evolve. You can also upgrade your weapons using workbenches, which are available in every Hideout.
column3: Якщо ви недостатньо сильні, пам'ятайте, що кров містян - це найшвидший спосіб розвинутися. Ви також можете поліпшити свою зброю на верстаку, який доступний у кожному укритті.

column2: Merchant’s prices for their goods may vary, depending on their district's health status.
column3: Merchant’s prices for their goods may vary, depending on their district's health status.

column2: Rat blood is not as nourishing or tasty as human, but it will partially refill your blood bar.
column3: Кров пацюків не така поживна і смачна, як людська, але вона частково поповнить ваш запас крові.

column2: Sick citizens can be healed with the appropriate treatment. A healthy citizen contributes to raising the Health Status of the district they belong to.
column3: Хворих містян можна зцілити з поміччю відповідних ліків. Здоровий містянин поліпшує стан здоров'я в районі, до якого він належить.

column2: Some Citizens may have quests for you if you talk to them. They’ll always reward your help!
column3: Деякі містяни мають для вас завдання, якщо ви з ними поговорите. Вони завжди винагородять вашу допомогу!

column2: Some Vampire Skills work better in Synergy with other Skills. Try out different Skill combinations, and perform deadly combos!
column3: Деякі вампірські вміння краще працюють у поєднанні з іншими навичками. Спробуйте різні комбінації навичок і виконуйте смертоносні комбо!

column2: Some enemies, including Blind Skals and Preachers, will feel your presence while using this ability.
column3: Деякі вороги, зокрема сліпі скали та проповідники, відчують вашу присутність під час використання цієї здатності.

column2: The amount of XP you get from Citizens you choose to Embrace is directly linked to their Blood Quality.
column3: The amount of XP you get from Citizens you choose to Embrace is directly linked to their Blood Quality.

column2: When looking for a Citizen, don’t forget your vampiric senses.
column3: Шукаючи містян, не забувайте про вампірські чуття.

column2: You can craft different kinds of Serums using a workbench. These can be lifesavers in dangerous combat situations.
column3: Ви можете створювати різні сироватки на верстаку. Вони можуть врятувати життя в небезпечних бойових ситуаціях.

column2: Use the workbenches in Hideouts to craft new treatments and serums, or to upgrade your weapons.
column3: Користуйтеся верстаком в укриттях, щоби створити нові ліки, сироватки або поліпшити зброю.

column2: You can heal aggravated damage by using your Autophagy ability, drinking human blood or resting.
column3: You can heal aggravated damage by using your Autophagy ability, drinking human blood or resting.

column2: You can upgrade and customize melee weapons and firearms using a workbench, to boost their efficiency.
column3: You can upgrade and customize melee weapons and firearms using a workbench, to boost their efficiency.

column2: If you’re not strong enough, remember that the blood of Citizens is the fastest way to evolve. You can also upgrade your weapons using workbenches, which are available in every Hideout.
column3: Якщо ви недостатньо сильні, пам'ятайте, що кров містян - це найшвидший спосіб розвинутися. Ви також можете поліпшити свою зброю на верстаку, який доступний у кожному укритті.

column2: You must rest in a bed to spend XP and evolve. Look for Hideouts!
column3: Ви повинні відпочити в ліжку, щоб витратити ОД та розвинутися. Знайдіть укриття!

column2: Your health regenerates slowly over time.
column3: Ваше здоров'я повільно відновлюється з часом.

column2: A pretty feminine handkerchief, with a persistent smell of jasmine perfume.
column3: Гарна жіноча хустинка, зі стійким запахом парфумів жасмину.

column2: Increase the rate of fire by 20%

It is with a heavy heart that I must report the murder of Sean Patrick Hampton, founder of the Hampton Asylum, and renowned benefactor of the East End. A parishioner who had come for morning mass found Sean at 6 a.m. Police are currently investigating the crime.<lf>It’s hard to imagine what might have motivated such villainy. Sean, also known as the 'Sad Saint,' was a philanthropist, a lover of mankind, who was deeply loved in return. A man of faith who devoted his life to nurse the poor and the sick. Aside from food and care, he also provided his flock with nourishment of the heart, and held regular masses for those that even the most altruistic Churches would reject. Sean will be missed dearly, and the consequences of his loss are already felt.<lf>Without his charisma, the closure of his night shelter was inevitable. Many people are now living in the cold, and contaminated streets. Without a roof, men and woman will get sick. Some will die, and no one will do anything. The murderer did not only take a life, he extinguished hope in a part of town that desperately needed it.<lf>Sean was a ray of hope in East End, and for having met him many times, I can affirm that his goodness extended past his faith. He was a good man, a truly good man. His loss is a catastrophe, and I cannot picture what sick mind, or deplorable turn of events might have brought this tragedy upon us. May the Sad Saint rest in peace and watch over our mediocre souls.<lf><lf>E.W.

Sean, also known as the 'Sad Saint,' was a philanthropist, a lover of mankind, who was deeply loved in return. A man of faith who devoted his life to nurse the poor and the sick. Aside from food and care, he also provided his flock with nourishment of the heart, and held regular masses for those that even the most altruistic Churches would reject. Sean will be missed dearly, and the consequences of his loss are already felt.<lf>Without his charisma, the closure of his night shelter was inevitable. Many people are now living in the cold, and contaminated streets. Without a roof, men and woman will get sick. Some will die, and no one will do anything. The murderer did not only take a life, he extinguished hope in a part of town that desperately needed it.<lf>Sean was a ray of hope in East End, and for having met him many times, I can affirm that his goodness extended past his faith. He was a good man, a truly good man. His loss is a catastrophe, and I cannot picture what sick mind, or deplorable turn of events might have brought this tragedy upon us. May the Sad Saint rest in peace and watch over our mediocre souls.<lf><lf>E.W.

column2: Some abilities are so powerful that even Vampires fear them. Blood Cauldron is one of them.  The Vampire concentrates their power on one target and makes the victim's blood boil. Through this process, the Vampire will regenerate, and absorb part of the target's blood.<lf>The Vampire will release their prey after a few seconds, leaving damaged Blood cells within them.  These Cells will continue to impact their host, before exploding after a short delay. The blast will affect any living creature near the host.<lf>Because of its dark nature, this type of ability cannot be used too often.<lf><lf>Controlling blood is one thing. Modifying the blood cells is another...""

column2: If you've ever lived near the Docks of East End, you must know who Sean Patrick Hampton is, and if not, you might have heard of him. His name is starting to spread through the entire capital, and the song it sings is one of hope.<lf>                  Sean is the humble founder of the Hampton Asylum, an establishment that he built with his own hands and convictions. The building, an abandoned warehouse gracefully donated by the Dawson family, then renovated and transformed into what is now the most famous asylum in London. The poor and hungry are welcome under his roof, and with them he shares his food, his care, and his prayers.<lf>                  Sean Hampton came from a background of misery, but the hardships of life didn't disfigure or maim his profound trust in the Lord. If anything, the faithful man gained an acute empathy in exchange for the torments of poverty. His love of others is renowned throughout the docks: rare are those who didn't witness Sean cry at the sight of an infirm veteran, an orphaned child, or a sick mother. That how he gained his nickname: “the Sad Saint of the East End”.<lf>                Sean Hampton is so respected that people still stay in his shelter, even after the Sad Saint contracted a mysterious disease which forces him to rest a lot, and take his meals away from his flock, while in some other parts of London, people step back as soon as someone coughs in public, men and women accept to eat and sleep in the Hampton Asylum. It’s the safest place in the East End Docks.<lf>                 The building looks dirty, the stench around the place is awful for a delicate soul, but there is hope and love there. And the death toll has been low, and stable for days.<lf><lf>E.W.

column2: Some abilities are so powerful that even Vampires fear them. Blood Cauldron is one such ability.<lf>The Vampire concentrates their power on one target and makes the victim's blood boil. Through this process, the Vampire will regenerate, and absorb part of the target's blood.<lf>The Vampire will release their prey after a few seconds, leaving damaging Blood cells within them.  These cells will continue to impact their host, before exploding after a short time. The blast will affect any living creature near the host.<lf>Because of its dark nature, this type of ability cannot be used too often.<lf><lf>Controlling blood is one thing. Modifying the blood cells is another...""

column2: For months, the Pembroke Hospital remained the only steadfast medical facility in the East End of London. This morning, the building irreversibly closed its doors. Local authorities, following a formal assessment of extreme squalor, ordered the facility shutdown. It seems the hospital helped the spread of disease.<lf>The Pembroke administration has yet to issue an official statement, but the extremely low number of people who left the hospital in good health during the last weeks corroborates the theory of mistreatment, and poor medical practice. With a capacity for little more than a hundred patients, the Pembroke was found to be housing more than three hundred, some more dead than alive, shoehorned into the rooms and even corridors of the hospital!<lf>Several honourable physicians had criticized the establishment prior to this catastrophe for the opacity of its financing arrangements. It is recommended, should you want to maintain your physical well being, to seek medical help with proven professionals elsewhere.<lf>S.L.A.<lf><lf>Disclaimer: today's New Londoner article was replaced by a contribution from our special reporter Solomon L. Anthelm. Your usual E.W. column will resume once redacted according to the regulations in effect.
column3: For months, the Pembroke Hospital remained the only steadfast medical facility in the East End of London. This morning, the building irreversibly closed its doors. Local authorities, following a formal assessment of extreme squalor, ordered the facility shutdown. It seems the hospital helped the spread of disease.<lf>The Pembroke administration has yet to issue an official statement, but the extremely low number of people who left the hospital in good health during the last weeks corroborates the theory of mistreatment, and poor medical practice. With a capacity for little more than a hundred patients, the Pembroke was found to be housing more than three hundred, some more dead than alive, shoehorned into the rooms and even corridors of the hospital!<lf>Several honourable physicians had criticized the establishment prior to this catastrophe for the opacity of its financing arrangements. It is recommended, should you want to maintain your physical well being, to seek medical help with proven professionals elsewhere.<lf>S.L.A.<lf><lf>Disclaimer: today's New Londoner article was replaced by a contribution from our special reporter Solomon L. Anthelm. Your usual E.W. column will resume once redacted according to the regulations in effect.

column2: YET MORE PROOF OF THE VIOLENCE AND DANGER THAT LURKS IN LONDON!<lf>A young nurse, Miss Dorothy Crane, was found dead yesterday morning, behind the walls of what seemed to be an illegal dispensary where the local sick sometimes went to get medical support from unidentified activists.<lf>                           There was no doubt about the cause of Miss Crane's passing: the poor woman had died from blood loss following what the police described as 'a massive wound to her throat.' That macabre scene was but the epitome of the current situation in Whitechapel: its inhabitants are criminals, bandits, or madmen disguised as citizens of London. Interestingly, no hospital admitted to have employed the victim.<lf>                          The dispensary has immediately been closed by decision of the London City Council’s Board of Health. As always, the soft and liberal minds already object that this closure of the only local medical facility can only increase the mortality rate, and put the locals’ health at further risk. One cannot help but dread the time when these peoples brutality will seep through the walls of the City itself. It is our role as civilized people to protect our families, our brethren, and of course, ourselves.<lf><lf>S.L.A.

column2: SERIAL CRIMES<lf>Last night, seven more murder victims were found near Saint Mary's Church, including its vicar, Mr. Joseph Larrabee, who was found dead in the adjoining cemetery. The clergyman had been savagely slaughtered and thrown into a half-exhumed grave, creating a scene of indescribable atrocity. It appeared that other tombs and crosses had also been broken and desecrated.<lf>They are the latest targets in a series of murders. Aside from the victims of gang raids in the East End (which, we have come to consider a normal occurrence), about twenty crimes were reported in the last few weeks in various boroughs. Crimes so violent and inhuman they reminded me of the butchery that struck us decades ago when the notorious, and still unidentified, Ripper prowled our streets.<lf>Witnesses also reported that some unidentified militia had been spotted in parts of the city, patrolling the streets and alleys at night without letting anyone approach them.<lf><lf>UNKNOWN MILITIA PATROL REPORTED<lf>Reliable witnesses also report that an unidentified militia has been spotted in some parts of town, patrolling the streets and alleys at night without letting anyone approach them for safety or sanitary reasons. Scotland Yard refused to comment on the matter, but admitted that no official military presence have been sent to patrol London’s boroughs.<lf>Who are these men and women, then? How, and why do they dare to openly carry guns? What are their objectives? Why operate at night? Are they some East End gang who decided to personally take care of local safety? Former soldiers who do not believe in quarantine lines anymore? Dedicated policemen trying to capture Joseph Larrabee’s murderer?<lf><lf>For now, we should assume that the beasts among us are unrestrained.<lf>Make sure to be accompanied should you want to go out at night, and make sure to take regular stock of loved ones, neighbours, and acquaintances.<lf><lf>Do not let anyone fall prey.<lf>E.W.

column2: REPORTS OF MYSTERIOUS DISAPPEARANCES HAVE ESCALATED IN THE PAST WEEKS!<lf>It has reached the point where witnesses have to queue before recounting their testimonies to an officer. Although this phenomenon appears to be a nationwide occurrence, the statements of the last twenty-four hours have converged around a single area in the country: Whitechapel, London!<lf>                 Yes, once more, the despised and loathed East End is left to struggle on its own. Continuously overlooked by the authorities, even while numerous families from this district report the unexplained disappearance of relatives, and neighbours. What has happened to these missing individuals? Where are they? The only link between them seems to be their health, and their need for urgent medical attention. Until recently, it was a local secret that the only place to get help was a discreet dispensary managed by unidentified good Samaritans. But the place now seems to be closed, and no one has any news from that facility. Did the missing persons go to a more secret place? Have they been discreetly moved to a more official service? One day soon, the London City Council’s Board of Health will have to answer for this new mystery.<lf><lf>E.W.

column2: You, with enough money to buy this paper, enough contempt to scoff at the title of this article, yet enough curiosity to read it anyway, should be informed about the truth of the so-called news you read in the press of London.<lf>Last night the Whitechapel district was evacuated following an abrupt rise in mortality rates. Thousands of inhabitants were hastily relocated, filling hospitals and wards that were already overflowing with terminally ill families, many in bad health, and most of them fearful after days and nights of silent terror. Will you read about this catastrophe elsewhere? No. Am I allowed to write about it? Even less so. Journalists are gagged, silenced, forbidden to raise awareness about the horror that dances before our very eyes.<lf>Hear me: London is falling. Protect yourself and your loved ones from this sickness, but do not close your eyes to it. It is here, and its thirst craves young and old, rich, and poor.<lf>Many thanks to my colleagues (whose names I will keep private for their own safety) who helped me bypass the censorship that is the true plague of London. I assume full responsibility for this publication and beg the authorities to end their insane control.<lf><lf>E.W.

column2: WHILE ALL HIS FRIENDS AND RELATIVES EXPECTED THE SAD NEWS OF HIS DEATH TO BE ANNOUNCED SOON, Aloysius Dawson, co-founder and head of the Dawson & Dawson company, has made an astonishing appearance at the last meeting of the London City Council’s Board of Health.<lf>For more than two hours, the supposedly dying magnate accused three members of the board of criminal carelessness, before demanding their immediate expulsion. Supported by Lord Redgrave, the Earl of Bristol, who assisted in the meeting, Aloysius was then ordained as the new administrator of the LCCBH. The very much living magnate immediately ordered the launch of his grand plan to save London: The creation of a quarantine wall around the West End, to protect the more affluent districts, and contain the Spanish Flu in the already impacted boroughs.<lf>Of course, many inhabitants of the targeted districts are now protesting vigorously, arguing that their health is more than ever at risk since the cases of infections can only grow in the quarantined areas. But that’s only because they lack the moral fibre of great men like Aloysius Dawson. Every nation, every empire, when facing a deadly peril, such as the Spanish Flu, must make sacrifices. It is by accepting these necessary sacrifices that the real patriots will serve the empire and its interests during these dark times.<lf><lf>S.L.A.

This ancient sword with a Latin phrase engraved on the blade, had been forged in Wales during the 6th century and belonged to Paulus Aurelianus, founder of the Brotherhood of Saint Paul's Stole. Legend says he had this blade forged before he chose the path of exile and left England with his people. Dragonbane has been passed to each new Primate of the Brotherhood, and may have been used in secret ceremonies, when a Primate was sent on a path of war to defeat a hostile creature. The sacred sword was supposedly lost during the schism between the Brotherhood and the Guard of Priwen in the middle of the 19th century. It seems a few copies may have been made, but this is the true and original Dragonbane.

column2: No, this catastrophe is no surprise! Since 2 am today, the Docks of the East End are officially segregated. The police report stated that ‘A sudden escalation in violence have forced the authorities to isolate the area.' Inhabitants were evacuated to temporary shelters.<lf>Since then, local authorities, and Scotland Yard have been juggling their responsibilities in this event: was it the fault of the gangs that bled out of the district, unopposed, or the rumoured madmen that killed the inhabitants, uncaught? No, it wasn't. Those who say this came off as a surprise are liars, blind men with the judgment of children. It wasn't the gangs: they have been part of our city for so long that crime is part of day-to-day life here. It wasn't a serial murderer: our physicians refuted the idea, identifying causes of death that ranged from old age and sickness, to homicide. No, it wasn't a single specific culprit, despite your hopes. It was you. Me. Everyone. Everyone foresaw this fall, and now, cowards that we are, we pretend to be astonished when faced with the inevitable. It is we, who did nothing, who should repent.<lf><lf>My thoughts go to friends, my neighbours, and to strangers alike. May you find your loved ones safe and well.<lf><lf>E.W.

column2: As of late, the rumours that surround Whitechapel are ripening into facts. In the last three months the police have suspected the district of hosting what might be the heart of London's medicinal black market.<lf>But of course, these suspicions will remain assumptions, for no task force or additional police presence has been sent to Whitechapel. No large drugs stocks have been found, nor no crime lords arrested. This masquerade has only been planned as a desperate attempt to conceal the blatant incompetence of the London City Council’s Board of Health, by giving the populace a cheap and easy victory, while the epidemic spreads more, and more each day. Worst of all, when you take time to review the most recent statistics, you discover that the district of Whitechapel is coping with the disease much better than other parts of the city. Is it a miracle? Evidence of the activity of an illegal, but efficient medical underground? More proof of the authorities’ criminal incompetence? All I know is this: if a Londoner has a better chance to survive the epidemic by choosing to live in this God-forsaken borough, I am ready to move to any cheap flea infested flat some shady landlord will agree to rent me, right now!<lf><lf>S.L.A.

column2: As I write these lines, the heart of London has stopped beating. This morning at 3 am, police forces organized the evacuation of thousands of residents, insisting on the urgent nature of the situation. Thieves and freaks having been driven mad with the fever were flooding our streets. Our forces were too few, and their crazed malice was too great! We are spread thin across London, and it is from a barricaded shelter that I write this dire report.<lf>What overran our beloved city? Was it the plague? That rumoured illness coming from the most forsaken parts of town. Or was it the Lord himself, telling us to flee a London that had become too corrupted, too unfaithful?<lf>Either way, our homes have burned, and nothing remains. Aloysius Dawson’s vision of the West End kept safe from the fiery menaces of outer London was proven right. A wall was the only thing that might have kept us from such violence! But it’s too late, now. So here we are, crying over lost children, siblings, and parents. Forced to wait for some sign of sanity, while surrounded by lunacy and anarchy! The West End has fallen. How can the country survive this tragedy?<lf><lf>S.L.A.

column3: Саліцин можна використовувати як анальгетик або протизапальну речовину. Він також може допомогти зменшити температуру. З початку епідемії в Лондоні нестача силіцину.

column2: The death of Aloysius Dawson, head of the Dawson Empire, occurred last night at around 4 am. One of his manor’s chambermaids found him in his bed this morning, bathed in his own blood. She immediately reported the incident to the police. A number of Mr. Dawson’s household staff are currently being interviewed, but a clear culprit has yet to be identified!<lf>Born in the City, Mr. Dawson had been a benevolent patron of London, and a faithful member of the Catholic Church for many years. He wore many hats: Tradesman, employer, father, and brother. The lucky few who knew him personally, myself included, knew that he was much more.  <lf>He was a man of vision! He saw a glistening future for our crime-ridden capital; he saw the ways through which our families and friends could be protected from the dangers outside; he saw how he, himself, as a man of wealth and influence, could use his fortune to the benefit of the people. Mr. Dawson had planned to turn the City into a fortress where the virtuous could live in peace. Sadly, this idea attracted the jealousy of others, and they did not let him live long enough to enjoy the fruit of his dedication.<lf>Mr. Dawson leaves a daughter, and many admirers to mourn his loss.<lf><lf>S.L.A.

column3: Вогонь - це наша зброя, браття. Найкращий спосіб знищити звіра - спалити його.

column3: The amount of XP you get from the Citizens you choose to Embrace is directly linked to their Blood Quality.

column2: Vampyr is centered on the choices you make. In dialogs, irrevocable choices are indicated by a red Y in the dialog circle. Choose wisely as you cannot take it back.
column3: Гра Vampyr зосереджена на ваших виборах. Під час розмов, безповоротний вибір позначається червоним Y у діалоговому колі. Вибирайте з розумом, оскільки ви не зможете його скасувати.

column2: We are no longer a part of the circle of life and death.We are undead, my friend, and so we are outcasts.
column3: Ми більше не є частиною кола життя та смерті. Ми неживі, друже мій, і тому ми є вигнанцями.

column3: Шукаючи містян, не забувайте про вампірські чуття.

column3: Ви можете зцілити серйозні пошкодження, використовуючи вміння «автофагія», випивши людської крові або відпочивши.

column2: You can put up to two markers on the map to help you find your way.
column3: Ви можете поставити до двох міток на мапі, які допоможуть знайти шлях.

column3: Ви можете відстежувати місцеве розслідування за допомогою спеціального меню, щоб воно з'явилося на карті.

column3: Ви можете поліпшувати та змінювати зброю ближнього бою або вогнепальну зброю за допомогою верстака, щоби підвищити її дієвість.

column2: What is immortality? Having your name inscribed in History, raising children who will honour your memory, earning your place among the saints of Heaven?<lf><lf>Sean Hampton, founder of the Hampton Asylum in East End, has his opinion on the matter: eternity comes to those who bear divine presence in themselves. Mr. Hampton, also known as the 'Sad Saint' for his unequalled empathy towards others, and his constant pity for their plight, has created with his Asylum a haven for lost souls. He keeps the poor fed and gives them a roof to sleep under.<lf>Still, the Asylum has now been closed for a few days and his last accessible orations took a turn towards cult-like worship. If heresy can be defined as faith gone adrift, Sean Hampton and his flock may have been turned into heretics. For the first time since I have know the Sad Saint, people speak ill of him, and the mysterious chants heard through the closed doors of the shelter worry more than they encourage.<lf>As a possible consequence of this suspicion, the sanitary situation of the Docks has drastically decreased. Deprived of a place to rest, the poor get sick from sleeping rough. Preferring to catch their death under the stars than join an unknown cult, that alone says enough of the tarnished reputation of the Sad Saint. A reputation that will be restored only when the doors of his Asylum open once again.<lf><lf> E.W.

column2: A HIGHLY RESPECTED RESIDENT OF THE CITY DISTRICT PASSED AWAY LAST NIGHT. Aloysius Dawson, co-founder and head of the Dawson & Dawson company, at 71 years of age.<lf>It was no secret that Mister Dawson’s health had recently declined. The once joyful businessman had almost totally disappeared from social events since the tragic death of his twin brother. An influential man, Aloysius Dawson was also a great art collector, and a concerned philanthropist. Recently, he had campaigned for an audacious plan to save London from the Spanish Flu, by raising a quarantine wall to separate the districts, and contain the epidemic. But only a few hours before his death, the magnate had given orders to cancel the construction of the wall. More surprisingly, large donations of money have been received by all major London hospitals, while equally important contributions have been made to the smaller clinics and dispensaries.<lf>Does it mean Aloysius Dawson, a man known for his fortitude and conservative opinions, was finally touched by grace? Who could say? Only one thing is certain: all over the city, thanks to that man’s late generosity, stocks of medical supplies have been replenished, and the death toll has significantly been lowered in the last twenty-four hours. No doubt hundreds of grateful citizens will be at the Saint Mary Churchyard to accompany the final journey of their benefactor.<lf><lf>S.L.A.

column2: The inhabitants of London live in fear of physicians. Delayed interventions, barefaced favouritism, and strange experimental treatments. This scarcity of professionalism is crystallized in Pembroke hospital, Whitechapel, where deontology was discharged a long time ago.<lf>The Pembroke administration hides behind a facade of dedication and rectitude, but those of us who know any of their patients, or worse, were among them, are aware of their deceit. In this temple devoted to dread, you will have to pay to get a bed. You will catch illnesses you never knew existed, and your corpse will be relieved of its possessions in the morgue. Here, patients die overnight of wounds they never bore upon their arrival... And they call them 'accidents.'<lf>I briefly interviewed Dr. Swansea, head of administration, declaimed a pedantic 'Timor mortis conturbat me' ('fear of death confounds me'), before forcing us out of the establishment.<lf>Quotes in Latin will not be enough to keep us away from their morbidity: volunteers are welcome to join me tomorrow morning in front of the hospital to demand clear facts about the state of this medical institution. Come in numbers.<lf><lf>E.W.

column2: THE DEATH RATE DROPS<lf>In a grand announcement spread across multiple newspapers this morning, the City Council lets the citizens of London know that the global death rate of the city (illness, old age, and crime) has finally started to drop.<lf>This declaration follows a troubling period during which suspicions of mass murder were being investigated. Although the butchers have yet to be identified, it's a relief to see that the killing spree has ended. The police force and citizens alike have teamed up to retake the more lawless parts of the city, and plans are being made to bring them back to life.<lf><lf>TO REBUILD LONDON<lf>Those in the know are saying that the new Dawson Foundation is entering into a contract with the City Council by which they will place the whole of their resources at the disposal of the authorities for the reconstruction of Greater London.<lf>The new scheme for the damaged districts include provisions for the construction of two new hospitals in Whitechapel, and the reopening of a revitalised Doris Fletcher Theatre to honour the memory of the late renowned London actress. Similar new institutions dedicated to culture, health, and faith are due to be erected in the coming years.<lf>Friends and relatives, too many died in the madness that took hold of London, and it is time for us to restore the city we know and love.<lf>This is my last New Londoner chronicle, and I wish my readers well.<lf>Volunteers are invited to join me tomorrow at the Mahogany, to discuss individual, and group efforts. I will personally organize this meeting, and the many others that will surely follow.<lf><lf>Come in numbers, friends.<lf><lf>E.W.
column3: THE DEATH RATE DROPS<lf>In a grand announcement spread across multiple newspapers this morning, the City Council lets the citizens of London know that the global death rate of the city (illness, old age, and crime) has finally started to drop.<lf>This declaration follows a troubling period during which suspicions of mass murder were being investigated. Although the butchers have yet to be identified, it's a relief to see that the killing spree has ended. The police force and citizens alike have teamed up to retake the more lawless parts of the city, and plans are being made to bring them back to life.<lf><lf>TO REBUILD LONDON<lf>Those in the know are saying that the new Dawson Foundation is entering into a contract with the City Council by which they will place the whole of their resources at the disposal of the authorities for the reconstruction of Greater London.<lf>The new scheme for the damaged districts include provisions for the construction of two new hospitals in Whitechapel, and the reopening of a revitalised Doris Fletcher Theatre to honour the memory of the late renowned London actress. Similar new institutions dedicated to culture, health, and faith are due to be erected in the coming years.<lf>Friends and relatives, too many died in the madness that took hold of London, and it is time for us to restore the city we know and love.<lf>This is my last New Londoner chronicle, and I wish my readers well.<lf>Volunteers are invited to join me tomorrow at the Mahogany, to discuss individual, and group efforts. I will personally organize this meeting, and the many others that will surely follow.<lf><lf>Come in numbers, friends.<lf><lf>E.W.
